GCMMF (Amul) won the 12th BML Munjal Award - 2017 for “Business Excellence through Learning and Development” in the Manufacturing - Public/Co-operative Sector category. The Award  & Citation were  received by our MD from  Shri Prakash Javadekar, Hon’ble Union Minister of Human Resource Development during the Mindmine Summit, an Annual Flagship event of Hero Enterprise, held in New Delhi on 20th April, 2017. 

The awards are named after the late Hero Group Chairman and Padma Bhushan Awardee Dr. Brijmohan Lal Munjal.  The annual BML Munjal Awards recognize organizations that have successfully deployed programs and implemented innovative strategies, processes and systems for learning and development, using people development as a tool to achieve Business Excellence. 

Amul demonstrates that business excellence can be achieved by imparting continuous learning and development programmes to its employees and stake holders, that benefit both the producers and the consumers. This award is a recognition of our various learning and development initiatives. 

The winners are selected by eminent Jury Panel Members through various  stages of evaluation processes.  The Jury comprised of  business stewards and leaders in various fields.

This is regarding the Facebook post that Ms Neha Tomar has shared on her wall. The details of the matter are as follows:

The consumer called our customer care on 10th morning at 9.22 am and shared her experience of using Amul Gold Milk on the very same day. She also emailed the complaint to our official email ID on 10th afternoon. As informed by her, the "use by" date of the Amul Milk was 9th of October. The milk got expired in her fridge which was later used by the consumer.

However, it may be noted that Ms Neha posted her grievance on her Facebook page on 9th October, a day prior to her informing us about the same. Ms Neha Tomar's post on Facebook on 9th Oct, screenshot attached.

Our officials asked the customer that if she has faced the problem on 10th Oct, how is it possible for you to post the same on 9th on Facebook? We now see that the timing of her post has been changed to 10th. 

On 11th, we visited her residence in Gurgaon and discussed the above. 
On 13th we once again visited the customer and provided technical reasons for the incident. We informed her that we checked all the batches of the same Amul Milk and found that there is no problem in any batches including the one which consumer had purchased.

As mentioned in her post, the consumer was trying to make cheese from sour milk which turned out to be a stretchy mass. Let us explain why this happened.

Any natural milk (branded/unbranded) which is acidified (sour) in the chilled condition and then heated shall result in curd mass which shows stretching property similar to that of mozzarella cheese. We have demonstrated the same in the video attached in which we have used fresh milk, acidified to the pH 5.2 and heated to obtain similar mass as shown by the complainant.
Video: http://goo.gl/kOJ74R

We do not understand that why the consumer used her official position to make such complaint without knowing the fact.

The customer when contacted and replacement was provided on 11th Oct, was requested to update her post with a clarification of her satisfaction with explanation provided by us. However it took more than 48 hours for the consumer to mention the same on her wall.  She even told that our officers that she will update the same post on 13th evening. But till time of posting this, it has not been updated with correct information. Also, the facts have been carefully concealed by her to generate and sustain the hype.

We wish to clarify that there has been absolutely no problem with the fresh milk that we supply in the market. Based on the misrepresentation of facts by the said consumer, we infer that the expired milk used by the complainant was deliberately abused to malign the brand. As a brand owned by 3.5 million milk producers, we are serving you from last six decades and we take utmost pride in the quality that we provide to you.

Amul dedicates this message to every Indian mother and her baby on the occasion of World Breastfeeding week (1st to 7th August):

Friendship. Freedom. Love. None of which can be canned and sold over any shop counter. So is the best baby food in the world: breast milk.

It’s the healthiest expression of your love and care for your baby. Just see it for yourself. Snug an secure in your arms, your baby enjoys it better than anything else. And nothing in the world can bring you and your little bundle of love closer than breastfeeding. To create and sustain a warm emotional bond that’s beyond any substitute food.

And no substitute food can match the natural formulation of breast milk. In easy to digest proteins. In natural minerals. In energizing sugar. In fact, breast milk contains everything, repeat everything, your baby needs to protect his/her health. Simply because it comes from you. 

And who else in the world could make it better than you, Ma?

Amul dedicates this message to every Indian mother and her baby on the occasion of World Breastfeeding week (1st to 7th August):

Glorious motherhood. Bliss. Contentment. Suddenly, the nine long months of minor and not so minor discomforts seem to be worth it all. “Listen, everybody. I’m a mother!”

It isn’t all quite so glorious with your body, though. Bringing forth a new life into life isn’t so easy. It’s a demanding task. And your body has just performed it. It needs help to recover from the weariness. 

The tired muscles need to relax. And the uterus to contract. Takes a little while for your body to come back to normal, pre-pregnancy health.

Breast-feeding helps. And when you breast-feed, two things happen. Your baby gets the best baby food in the world. And your tired body muscles revive to the gentle pleasure generated by your baby’s sucking. 

Well, call it the beauty of the best bringing back the best.

Amul dedicates this message to every Indian father and his baby on the occasion of World Breastfeeding week (1st to 7th August):

Every mother with a new born baby needs a little support. And the best man to provide it is you. Especially when she provides your baby with the best baby food in the world: breast milk.

Breast milk is indispensable to your baby. And happiness is indispensable to the breast-feeding mother. Stress and depression may dry up her milk. Would you like to see your baby denied of the best baby food in the world?

So keep your wife happy. And her spirits high. Breast-feeding is necessary for her body to recover from the post –labour weariness too. And she needs plenty of rest and relaxation. It helps her breastfeed better. So pitch in. Make yourself a little more useful around home. Take over some of the chores. With a smile.

Because the best baby food in the world needs a caring father too.

On the occasion of World Breastfeeding week (1st to 7th August), Amul dedicates this message to every Indian mother and her baby:

"IN FACT, THE BEST BABY FOOD IN THE WORLD IS MADE BY YOUR OWN BABY.

Quite surprisingly, your hungry baby ensures there is plenty of the best baby food in the world: breast milk.
And your breasts respond well to your baby’s needs. So well, in fact, that your baby’s hunger wails are sometimes enough to contract the muscle fibers around your milk glands and start the milk flowing. And the more your baby sucks, the more milk is made. And the more often your baby sucks milk, the quicker the replenishment is made. So if you’ve a hungry baby, relax you’ve more milk.
And you can’t wish for anything better. Because breast milk contains everything, repeat everything, your baby needs for better health. No substitute food can match it for natural proteins, minerals or sugar. And breast-feeding brings you and your baby closer. An emotional togetherness.
And together, you can never run short of the world’s best baby food too."

Amul wins AIMA High performance Brand award-2013.

The award will be presented during AIMA's 58th Foundation Day and National Management Day, scheduled to be held on 21st February 2014, at New Delhi. The award presentation ceremony will be held during a special plenary session. Mr. R S Sodhi, Managing Director, will receive the award on behalf of 3.5 million farmers of GCMMF who own “Amul” brand.

All India Management Association (AIMA), the national apex body of management profession in the country is committed to enhancing the competence of management profession through its multifaceted activities. Every year, to recognize excellence in Management, Entrepreneurship and Leadership, AIMA confers Awards on distinguished professional and organizations who have made outstanding contribution. To recognize and celebrate the marketing success of a brand, AIMA and R K SWAMY BBDO instituted the "AIMA - R K Swamy High Performance Brand Award" in 2009.
 
For the year 2013, Mr. Srinivasan Swamy, Jury Chairman & past President, AIMA along with other distinguished corporate leaders unanimously decided to bestow award on brand “Amul” of Gujarat Co-operative Milk Marketing Federation Ltd. (GCMMF).

Amul receives Green Globe Foundation Award 

The Gujarat Cooperative Milk Marketing Federation Ltd. (GCMMF) -  India’s largest food products marketing organization and apex body of dairy cooperatives of Gujarat – has won the “Green Globe Foundation Award” in the Manufacturing Category at the Delhi Sustainable Development Summit 2012 .  Mr. R.S. Sodhi, Managing Director, GCMMF Ltd. received the award in a glittering ceremony organized in association with TERI and United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP) at the Taj Palace Hotel, New Delhi on 2nd February, 2012.  

The 4th Green Globe Awards ceremony at the 12th Delhi Sustainable Development Summit 2012 was organized to facilitate the organizations and individuals working towards a cleaner environment and sustainable development.  Introducing the event, Dr. R K Pachauri, Director General, TERI said that the Green Globe Awards were important to recognize the initiatives of those who were working towards saving the planet.  

GCMMF received this award for its mass tree plantation drive and contribution to environment by the milk producers of Gujarat.  The 30 lac milk producers of Gujarat have planted more than 312 lakh trees in 15000 villages of the State in last 5 years.  Thus Amul has shown its concern, awareness and commitment for betterment of environment and has set an example for all the cooperatives and other institutions to turn India green in the era of global warming and environmental crisis.  

GCMMF is India’s largest food products marketing organisation with an annual sales turnover of Rs. 12,000 crores (US $ 2.4 bn). It procures an average of 100 lac litres of milk every day from 30 lac farmers across 15,000 villages of Gujarat.

GCMMF has been awarded Economic Times Excellence Award for the Best Corporate Citizen of the year 2011, for the contribution in making India, the largest milk producing nation in the entire world. This certainly is a matter of immense pride for all of us and is a recognition of the highly significant contribution of Amul cooperative movement, towards nation-building. This prestigious award is a tribute to our 3 million farmer-members of Gujarat who are part of the Amul family. 
ET awards for corporate excellence are among the most prestigious awards

Amul sponsors Sauber F1 Team in India

India’s largest food brand Amul is the official partner of Sauber F1 team at the inaugural Indian Grand Prix. Monisha Kaltenborn, Chief Executive of the Sauber F1 Team, said: “We are proud that we can announce this partnership with Amul, one of India’s leading brands. Amul products are present in practically every household. Having spent my childhood in Dehradun, India, I have fond memories of Amul, especially the Amul butter.”

R S Sodhi, Managing Director, Gujarat Cooperative Milk Marketing Federation Ltd.,  welcomed Sauber F1 Team to the first ever F1 Grand Prix in India. Talking about the Amul’s sponsorship of a F1 Team, Mr Sodhi said that milk is the healthiest natural beverage known to mankind since time immemorial. We could not have lost this opportunity to showcase this to the world at first ever F1 race in India, the largest producer of milk in the world. 

The association with Sauber F1 Team will enhance the Asia’s largest milk brand -Amul’s global brand presence. Currently, there is no food brand associated with any F1 team with on-car presence. 

Amul logo will appear prominently on the two Sauber F1 Team race cars the rear wing front face and the drivers’ helmets. Several product integrations too are being planned.

Visit of Shri Lal Bahadur Shastri, the then Prime Minister of India on 31st October, 1964. He formally  commissioned the Cattle Feed plant.  His visit inspired the formation of NDDB (National Dairy Development Board) and the Operation Flood programme.

It was the first time anywhere in the world that cheese and baby food was being processed from buffalo milk on a large commercial scale. The plant was inaugurated in 1960 by Shri Morarjibhai Desai, who was then India’s Finance Minister.

Three Prime Ministers of India in a photo:
Pt. Jawaharlal Nehru, Smt. Indira Gandhi, Shri Morarji Desai, Shri Tribhuvandas Patel and Dr. V. Kurien during inauguration of Amul Dairy on 31st October, 1955
India got Independence  on 15th August, 1947
On December 14, 1946 Kaira District Cooperative Milk Producers’ Union Ltd. (Amul Dairy) was registered.

Established two milk cooperative societies in October, 1946 – Hadgud and Gopalpura.  Hadgud was registered as an affiliate primary cooperative on October 7, 1946 and the first milk collection from there was made that very day
